NNOOTTEESS
       Since  ssttrrttooll()  can legitimately return 0, LLOONNGG__MMAAXX,
       or LLOONNGG__MMIINN (LLLLOONNGG__MMAAXX or LLLLOONNGG__MMIINN for ssttrrttoollll()) on
       both  success and failure, the calling program should
       set _e_r_r_n_o to 0 before the call, and then determine if
       an  error  occurred  by  checking whether _e_r_r_n_o has a
       nonzero value after the call.

       According to POSIX.1, in locales other than  "C"  and
       "POSIX",  these functions may accept other, implemen‐
       tation-defined numeric strings.

       BSD also has

           qquuaadd__tt ssttrrttooqq((ccoonnsstt cchhaarr **_n_p_t_r,, cchhaarr ****_e_n_d_p_t_r,, iinntt _b_a_s_e));;

       with completely analogous definition.   Depending  on
       the wordsize of the current architecture, this may be
       equivalent to ssttrrttoollll() or to ssttrrttooll().

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       The program shown below demonstrates the use of  ssttrr‐‐
       ttooll().   The  first command-line argument specifies a
       string from which ssttrrttooll()  should  parse  a  number.
       The  second (optional) argument specifies the base to
       be used for the conversion.  (This argument  is  con‐
       verted to numeric form using aattooii(3), a function that
       performs no error checking and has a  simpler  inter‐
       face  than  ssttrrttooll().)   Some examples of the results
       produced by this program are the following:

           $ ..//aa..oouutt 112233
           strtol() returned 123
           $ ..//aa..oouutt ''    112233''
           strtol() returned 123
           $ ..//aa..oouutt 112233aabbcc
           strtol() returned 123
           Further characters after number: "abc"
           $ ..//aa..oouutt 112233aabbcc 5555
           strtol: Invalid argument
           $ ..//aa..oouutt ''''
           No digits were found
           $ ..//aa..oouutt 44000000000000000000
           strtol: Numerical result out of range

   PPrrooggrraamm ssoouurrccee

       #include <stdlib.h>
       #include <limits.h>
       #include <stdio.h>
       #include <errno.h>

       int
       main(int argc, char *argv[])
       {
           int base;
           char *endptr, *str;
           long val;

           if (argc < 2) {
               fprintf(stderr, "Usage: %s str [base]\n", argv[0]);
               exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
           }

           str = argv[1];
           base = (argc > 2) ? atoi(argv[2]) : 0;

           errno = 0;    /* To distinguish success/failure after call */
           val = strtol(str, &endptr, base);

           /* Check for various possible errors */

           if (errno != 0) {
               perror("strtol");
               exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
           }

           if (endptr == str) {
               fprintf(stderr, "No digits were found\n");
               exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
           }

           /* If we got here, strtol() successfully parsed a number */

           printf("strtol() returned %ld\n", val);

           if (*endptr != '\0')        /* Not necessarily an error... */
               printf("Further characters after number: \"%s\"\n", endptr);

           exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
       }

